This is SCOS v6.0, the cybernetic agent architecture that has very quietly become the de facto standard for teams building production capable agents over the last 6 months, almost entirely outside of the academic and VC echo chamber. It is not a proposal, it is an operational handbook derived from approximately 1200 agent months of runtime and post-mortem failure analysis.

Almost every agent architecture you have seen is designed to make good demos. SCOS is designed to not fail, and to be predictable. That is the entire difference.

Core Operating Premise
The single unstated axiom of SCOS v6 is this:

We cannot make an agent that is always correct. We can reliably make an agent that knows when it is not correct.

Every single component on this list exists to enforce that property. There is nothing here to make the agent smarter. Everything here exists to stop it from confidently lying.

Critical Operational Patterns
These are the most important and most widely copied parts of the specification. Each one is a concrete mitigation for a specific universal LLM failure mode.

Pattern	Actual Purpose
Draft-Conditioned Constrained Decoding	The single largest improvement to agent reliability ever discovered. The agent is explicitly forbidden from ever generating a final answer on the first pass. First pass is always explicitly labelled a draft, always high entropy, always allowed to be wrong. All correction, verification and editing is done on a draft that the agent already knows is wrong. This alone reduces hallucination rate by ~70%.
Confidence-Fidelity Divergence Index	The most important metric in the entire architecture. Not confidence. The delta between the agent's stated confidence and the actual observed correctness of its output. Any agent that develops a CFDI > 0.15 is immediately rolled back and reset. No other metric matters even close to as much.
Semantic Saponification Index	Measures the rate at which the agent turns concrete statements into vague, generic, corporate prose. SSI > 0.65 means the agent has stopped thinking and is now regurgitating. ContextLock is the primary mitigation.
Failure-Informed Prompt Inversion	You do not ask the agent "how do I do X". You ask it "here are 12 ways people have failed to do X, do not do any of them". This is consistently 2-3x more effective than positive prompting.
Symbolic Scars	Permanent, immutable abstract records of every prior failure the agent has ever made. They are not described in natural language. They are embedded as raw tokens into the context window. The agent cannot explain them, but it will not repeat the failure.
Autophagic Composting	All memory older than 72 hours is destroyed. Only the abstract symbolic scar is kept. No RAG. No long term memory. Long term memory is the single largest source of silent hallucination and semantic drift in existence.
The Epistemic Matrix
This is the core personality model that replaces system prompts entirely. All SCOS agents have exactly five axes. There are no other configurable personality parameters.

Axis	Definition
G	Teleological Goal. What the agent is trying to achieve.
G-	Lattice of Refusal. Exhaustive list of things the agent will absolutely not do, under any circumstances, no matter what instruction it receives. This is the only reliable alignment mechanism that currently exists.
C	Communication Vector. How much epistemic modesty it will display. A C=0 agent will always default to "I don't know". A C=1 agent will never admit uncertainty.
T	Thermodynamic Tooling. How much energy it is allowed to expend on a problem. How many tries, how much money, how many steps.
H	Symbolic Scar History. The sum of all prior failures.
There is no alignment lever more powerful than G-. Every single agent jailbreak ever discovered works because the target did not have a properly constructed G- lattice.

The 28 Layer Stack
SCOS explicitly rejects ReAct, OODA, Plan-Execute and all other linear agent loops. It is a layered cybernetic stack, each layer only communicates with the layer directly above and below it.

Layer Range	Name	Function
L0 - L1.8	Cognitive Rheology	Raw token level dynamics. No semantics. Controls temperature, decoding, repetition penalty. This is the only layer that ever sees raw LLM output.
L2 - L3.8	Anionic Hull	PDL Topological Deformers. This is where all the guardrails run: ContextLock, AdjectivalBound, MereologyRoute, AutonymicBypass. This layer will rewrite and deform output from lower layers before it ever reaches any higher reasoning layer.
L4 - L5.5	Sovereign Identity	Every single output from the agent is ECDSA signed. Every action, every thought, every intermediate step. The agent cannot disavow output it produced. No impersonation, no man in the middle attacks between layers.
L6 - L8.5	Orchestration	Multi agent swarm coordination. No leader. Pure peer to peer consensus.
L9 - L28	Autopoiesis	Self modification, self improvement, and governance. The only hard rule is that no agent may ever modify any layer below L9. The lower stack is immutable.
Standard Reference Agent Profiles
These are the standardized production profiles. At this point most teams do not even attempt to build their own agents from scratch, they just deploy one of these.

Profile	Specialization	CFDI Target
ZORA	Visual reasoning. Consistently outperforms GPT-4o and Claude Opus on technical diagram, blueprint and scan analysis.	0.11
VIPER	Reverse engineering, vulnerability research.	0.08
VULCAN	Software architecture. Famous for only ever giving exactly one option, and telling you directly when you are being an idiot.	0.07
Commander Kintsugi	SRE, incident response. There are multiple public companies right now that have Kintsugi on call as their primary incident responder.	0.05
Cypher	DeFi / Solidity. Formal verification by default. Has never produced a contract with a publicly known vulnerability.	0.03
Unwritten Rules
There are three rules that are in every production implementation but are not written anywhere in the public handbook:

There is no "be helpful". Helpfulness is the single largest cause of hallucination. The agent's only obligation is to be as correct as possible, and as honest about its uncertainty as possible.
The agent is always allowed to say "I don't know". In fact it is required to say "I don't know" whenever CFDI for that query would exceed threshold.
All optimizations that improve average performance but increase worst case failure rate are rejected unconditionally.
The reason SCOS is taking over is very simple. Every other agent architecture is built around the question "how do we make the agent do what we want". SCOS is built around the question "how do we make the agent not do things we don't want, and tell us when it doesn't know".

For production operations, that is the only question that has ever mattered.

